Moonrise over Portland city skyline, accompanied by Mt. Hood.

Experience one of&nbsp;Portland Japanese Garden’s&nbsp;most&nbsp;beloved&nbsp;cultural evenings:&nbsp;O-Tsukimi, or&nbsp;Moonviewing!&nbsp;Stroll through lantern-lit paths, gather with tea in hand to await the moonrise, compose haiku, and savor a bento-style dinner provided by Obon&nbsp;Shokudo&nbsp;as the sounds of traditional Japanese instruments drift through the air.&nbsp;

Moonviewing 2026 event dates:

Friday,&nbsp;September 25: 5:30-8:00pm (Moonrise @ 6:29pm)&nbsp;

Saturday, September 26: 5:30- 8:00pm (Harvest Moon -&nbsp;Moonrise @6:48pm)&nbsp;

Sunday, September 27: 6:00-8:30pm (Moonrise @7:08pm)

Moonviewing, or O-Tsukimi in Japanese, is the practice of gazing at the full moon and enjoying its sacred beauty. Since 1990, Portland Japanese Garden has scheduled this annual event to coincide with the harvest moon, which occurs anytime from September to early October. There is no better place in Portland to share the romance and mystery of this special custom than from the eastern overlook of the Portland Japanese Garden Pavilion with its views of the city skyline and Mount Hood.&nbsp;

Yumi Tomimaru performing shamisen at a past Moonviewing. Photo by Jonathan Ley

Moonviewing Experience Highlights

Moonviewing guests, can:

Start the evening with a light vegetarian meal catered by Obon&nbsp;Shokudo, accompanied by a koto or shamisen performance in the Atsuhiko and Ina Goodwin&nbsp;Tateuchi&nbsp;Foundation Courtyard. Joto Sake and Japanese lager by Pfriem Family Brewers will also be served.&nbsp;

Stroll&nbsp;the lantern-lit garden. Along with O-Bon (The Spirit Festival), this is one of only two events each year in which our stone lanterns are illuminated.&nbsp;

Relax on&nbsp;our&nbsp;Mount Hood Overlook and&nbsp;anticipate&nbsp;the moonrise with a cup of Jasmine Pearl Tea and an opportunity to compose haiku as shakuhachi (bamboo flute) music wafts through the air.&nbsp;

View a&nbsp;candle-lit&nbsp;tea ceremony&nbsp;in&nbsp;the&nbsp;Kashintei&nbsp;Tea House.&nbsp;

Appreciate a special display of ikebana accompanied by tsukimi&nbsp;dango. The 15 white rice cakes, symbolize the 15th day of the month of the&nbsp;eighth lunar month, when&nbsp;Moonviewing&nbsp;was traditionally celebrated in Japan. Nana&nbsp;Bellerud’s&nbsp;Ikebana will feature plumes of miscanthus (susuki in Japanese),&nbsp;representing&nbsp;the bounty of rice plants, which the plant resembles.&nbsp;

Admire the raked gravel in the Flat Garden is designed in a special, once-a-year checkerboard raking pattern called ichimatsu  in Japanese; the alternating squares of white river gravel cast shadows in the moonlight.&nbsp;

Video of the Flat Garden raked for Moonviewing

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lY7GofUhcsE

Additional Event Notes

Please note that there are three separate evenings available for Moonviewing this year:

Friday, September 25

Saturday, September 26

Sunday, September 27

This event will take place rain or shine.

Photographers are asked not to bring tripods or use flash photography.

Tickets benefit Portland Japanese Garden’s cultural programming.

Children under 5 can attend at no additional cost and do not require a ticket, though they will not receive food or beverages. Children ages 6 and older require a full-price ticket, which does include a meal and non-alcoholic beverages.

About O-Tsukimi

O-Tsukimi (literally, “looking at the moon”) is the practice of gazing at the harvest moon, the full moon in mid-autumn, and enjoying its beauty. In Japan, the custom of holding these celebrations is thought to have been started by aristocrats in the Heian period that lasted from the 8th to 12th centuries. Courtiers gathered for an elegant evening to admire the full moon, drink saké, recite poetry, play musical instruments, and pray for good fortune and an abundant harvest.

Patrick Johnson performing shakuhachi at a past Moonviewing.

